post_text:
Our new and remodeled facilities will be ready for students when they arrive next week! We're proud to introduce you to the new Andover High School and Meadowlark Elementary; Andover CAPS - Center for Advanced Professional Studies; and additions and remodeling at Andover Middle School and Andover Central Middle School. These are in addition to Jaguar Stadium and the Andover Public Schools Tennis Complex, which also have opened this fall.

We can't say "thank you" enough to our community for supporting these incredible additions to our facilities, and the opportunities they will provide to our students!

post_text: Thank you to the Andover KS Police Department for helping to keep our students safe!
shared_text:
Andover KS Police Department
September 1 at 11:48 AM ·

ATTENTION ANDOVER RESIDENTS AND VISITORS!
Beginning 9/8/2020, schools in Andover will be starting the new school year and the men and women of the Andover Police Department, in cooperation with USD-385 School District and Durham School Services, would like to remind drivers to slow down in our school zones, and make sure they STOP for our school buses when the red lights are flashing and the STOP sign is extended! Officers will be in and around school zones to make sure everyone is driving safely and obeying the school bus stop laws.
Please keep our children safe! Obey the law!

Tonight, we are sending you the first draft of our Family Playbook for 2020-21. This document is the result of hard work by teachers, nurses, principals, district administrators and others who are committed to creating the safest possible school environment for the year.

Some of the information in the family playbook is pending approval by the Andover Board of Education during its meeting on Monday. Also, please know that this playbook will continue to evolve as we add resources and as conditions change in our community’s health situation during the year. We want this to be a “living” document and a place that you can go for the latest information about the school year. As we continue to update you during the year, we will let you know of significant changes or additions that are made to this playbook.

As always, we appreciate your partnership and support of your child’s education.

post_text:
Due to high interest, Thursday's Board of Education meeting will be livestreamed on the district's website at www.usd385.org/boe. Board members will hear reports on a proposed 2020-21 calendar, learning models, safety and other logistics for the 2020-21 school year. Board members will then discuss and likely take action on the plans for the year.

The meeting begins at 5 p.m. at the Andover Central High School Auditorium, and masks will be required of all who attend in person. We would encourage all of those who can to watch the livestream version to better ensure social distancing. More information about the year's plans will be sent after Thursday's meeting.

It wasn't the way we originally planned it.

It took flexibility, creativity and resilience.

And with that, more than 450 seniors at Andover High School (Kansas), Andover Central High School Jaguars and Andover Ecademy crossed the stage last week to be honored as part of the graduating Class of 2020. We had three beautiful nights for our celebrations.

Thank you to Hutton for donating this video to honor our seniors, and to Adler Grey Videography for producing it.

Congratulations, Trojans, Jaguars and Eagles!

post_text:
This tribute left at Andover Central High School Jaguars this evening perfectly encapsulates English teacher Mr. Patrick Kennedy: His popular "shout-out" videos to celebrate successes; his love for Converse sneakers; and most importantly, his ability to make meaningful connections with students.

Mr. Kennedy passed away Wednesday, apparently of natural causes. ACHS, his previous school Andover Central Middle School, and our entire district will miss him dearly. Thank you, Mr. Kennedy. #improudofyou #shoutout

post_text:
May 4-8 marks Teacher Appreciation Week this year. While we always celebrate our teachers during this annual observance, this year we’d like to do something special online, given our circumstances.

Our teachers have been put in a situation they never expected to be in, teaching remotely and working harder than ever to prepare lessons, deliver knowledge and keep students engaged.

To honor teachers, we are encouraging students and parents to submit short videos answering the question, “Why is my teacher awesome?” We plan to share these videos on social media during Teacher Appreciation Week.

Please email your video(s) to info@usd385.org by Friday, May 1. Please include your or your student’s first name, their teacher’s name, and school. Thank you for helping us celebrate our teachers!

post_text: Look at these graduates of Andover Central High School Jaguars doing us proud, especially at a time when heathcare providers are so important to our country. Way to go, Josh and Jacob!
shared_text:
KU School of Medicine-Wichita
April 10 at 12:53 PM ·

Two of our pediatric residents have close ties – they’re siblings. Neither Josh nor Jacob Umscheid planned on becoming a doctor after high school (they didn’t plan on wearing matching shirts for this photo, either).

Both earned the title of M.D. at KU School of Medicine-Wichita and accepted residencies in our Pediatric Residency Program. It was medical school and their residencies that brought them back to the Wichita area where they grew up.

Read the full story: bit.ly/2Jv4hJ4 #NationalSiblingsDay #JayhawkDocs

post_text: Thank you, Andover KS Police Department, for providing this service for our community!
shared_text:
Andover KS Police Department
March 25 at 1:56 PM ·

“BOOKS WITH BLUE” During this crazy time, like we have never seen before, with our schools and many business closed, and many people sheltering at home including children, beginning this afternoon (3/25/2020), the Andover Police Department will begin “Books with Blue.” Each week day, around 2:00 pm, the Department will post a video of one of our officers reading a short story. The book read each day will be an appropriate K-5 grade level book coordinated through our very own Andover Public Library. Most books read will be between 3 and 10 minutes in length.

Our hope is that our children will enjoy these videos, and maybe even some of our adults! And we ask that you share this information with others who might not be followers of the department’s Facebook page!

post_text:
Today has been quite the day. We know you have questions. We do, too.

Please send your questions to info@usd385.org. We will be gathering them and answering them in the coming days as we get clarity about our situation and make plans for the coming weeks.

Until then, please know:
- It's OK to feel uncertainty. These are unprecedented times that have evolved quickly. We're all in this together.
- We know it's difficult to talk to your kids about the change in the school year. We will work to send you some suggestions for how to make sense of this.
- We have empathy for lost opportunities these changes will bring.

We are here for your children. That does not change. That will not change.

Take care of yourselves, and each other, and we'll get through this together.

Congratulations to Alia Michaelis, a senior at Andover High School, a recipient of a Rudd Foundation scholarship worth $88,000 to attend Wichita State University. She is one of 30 Rudd Scholars this year. The scholarships go to Pell Grant-eligible students who have shown grit, determination and work ethic.

Alia hopes to major in biomedical engineering with a minor in Spanish at WSU. She is the second Rudd Scholar at AHS in three years. We're proud of you!

post_text:
Congratulations to Hillary Barscewski, first-grade teacher at Cottonwood Elementary, who has been named a Kansas Master Teacher by The Teachers College at Emporia State University. The honor goes to educators who have "served the profession long and well and also typify the good qualities of earnest and conscientious teachers."

Only seven Master Teachers are named each year. Ten Andover educators have been named Master Teachers since 2000. We're proud of you, Mrs. B!

Big day in Andover! Two educators — Keegan Hallmark of Andover Middle School and Victoria Bay of Andover Central Middle School — were named Horizon Award winners by the Kansas State Department of Education. The award goes to outstanding teachers in their second year in the classroom.

Mr. Hallmark, who teaches sciences, and Miss Bay, a social studies teacher, received a phone call from Dr. Randy Watson, Kansas Commissioner of Education, to learn the news. We're proud of our awesome educators!

When: 6 p.m. January 8
Where: Prairie Creek Elementary or Robert Martin Elementary
What: Learn about our programs (including our new full-day, five-day a week class), tour classrooms, meet teachers and more

We offer high-quality programs designed to ignite an interest in learning and prepare our students for kindergarten success. Come be part of the fun!

Our (soon-to-be) new athletics facilities officially have new names, thanks to Board of Education action Monday. Let's welcome:

- Jaguar Stadium, home of Andover Central High School Jaguars and Andover Central Middle School (open fall 2020).
- Trojan Stadium (facility currently known as District Stadium), to be renamed in fall 2020 when it becomes the official home of Andover High School and Andover Middle School.
- Andover Public Schools Tennis Complex (open fall 2020).
- Andover Public Schools Aquatics Center (open 2021).

Let's go Trojans and Jaguars!

(Pictured: Andover Public Schools Tennis Complex and Jaguar Stadium site.)

post_text:
Lots of good news to share at our Board of Education meeting tonight! Board members:

- Listened music from a small string ensemble that is a precursor to the district implementing an orchestra program in the 2020-21 school year.
- Heard about the Saturday History Academy, which brings more than 200 students from Andover and the surrounding area to learn about historical topics through primary documents.
- Sampled a s'more dessert prepared by culinary arts students at Andover Central High School. Teacher Lacey Woods is working to tie in student success skills such as communication and time management into her classes.

Cool classroom connection: Students in Michelle Snyder's graphic design class at Andover High School recently met with first-graders in Natasha Hinz's class at Cottonwood Elementary. The big kids learned about the little ones, specifically their hobbies and interests.

Today, the graphic design students presented the first-graders with their own framed, personalized artwork about themselves. They also shared pizza and talked about the holidays. What great role models for the younger students! #ExploreEngageEmpower

Rotary Club of Andover
December 6, 2019 at 10:27 AM ·

Presenters today were four 5th grade students from Cottonwood Elementary School. They reported on their recent experience at Starbase, which is a DOD science youth program and was held once a week over five weeks at McConnell AFB. They also wanted to thank the club for helping to transport them there over the course of the program. We are happy to hear you really enjoyed your experience!
